            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "General Rule of Thumb:\nMultiply repair cost by roof age in years. If the result exceeds $5,000, replacement typically makes better financial sense.\n\nExamples:\n- $1,200 repair on 3-year-old roof = $3,600 (repair makes sense)\n- $1,800 repair on 4-year-old roof = $7,200 (approaching replacement consideration)\n- $900 repair on 7-year-old roof = $6,300 (borderline, consider other factors)\n- $2,500 repair on 2-year-old roof = $5,000 (repair, but investigate why new roof failing)\n- $1,000 repair on 8-year-old roof = $8,000 (seriously consider replacement)\n\nThis formula accounts for reality that older roofs will need increasing repairs, and money spent patching aging systems might be better invested in new roof providing decades of trouble-free service."
